delayed-walking-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Delayed walking in children"},{"id":"f63a11de-e155-5afe-a226-402d885f4423","slug":"limp-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Limp in children"},{"id":"da28c3e0-278d-5fce-8968-bdc734d3e305","slug":"out-toeing","fullItemName":"Scenario: Out-toeing"},{"id":"3130a07e-303c-5b73-838c-5d6307fdead8","slug":"tip-toe-walking","fullItemName":"Scenario: Tip toe walking"}]},{"id":"086fd10d-b722-534e-b18d-5a0a2d5792c9","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bf424233-1954-55a8-98de-834693dbdd11","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"6728c56f-47a6-56f1-be0e-22c22275d9e9","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"2d75ec25-86dd-542a-b968-a3f7e80d0210","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2514c9ed-51af-51be-8f7d-3a997605efe6","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"6bdf3ba0-4bec-595d-bb71-c68f7fcb7c9c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"20bd862c-7ca7-5a5b-8f5d-443cd0bea04c","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"b747cefd-4366-540b-87c3-72fdbb926a30","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"8d402bd6-6ff7-597f-8744-fe50598828b1","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"70c6edae-9f69-59d1-8cb3-ca0d90950bdc","slug":"in-toeing","fullItemName":"In-toeing","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field cf637721-f8c2-4b8b-9647-aa0d00e65b15 --><h3>When should I consider referring a child with in-toeing?</h3><!-- end field cf637721-f8c2-4b8b-9647-aa0d00e65b15 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3c22241d-80eb-4304-89d7-aa0d00e65b15 --><!-- begin field 6613e968-61f9-4b8a-9b8e-aa0d00e65b15 --><ul><li><strong>Management in the community (for example by a physiotherapist or podiatrist with paediatric expertise) is usually appropriate for a child with in-toeing if <em>all </em>of the following are present: </strong><ul><li>The child is well with no <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flag</a> features and is aged less than 10 years.<strong> </strong></li><li>There is:<ul><li>No pain. </li><li>No limp or functional impairment. </li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Consider referring children with in-toeing for specialist assessment, using clinical judgement to determine the urgency, if <em>any</em> of the following are present:</strong><ul><li>A <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flag</a> feature.</li><li>Sudden onset of in-toeing. </li><li>Associated pain. </li><li>Extreme or persistent changes. </li><li>Unilateral or asymmetric intoeing.<strong> </strong></li><li>Limp, daily recurrent trips or falls, or functional problems. </li><li>Delayed developmental milestones. </li><li>Significant history for an underlying metabolic, neuromuscular, or orthopaedic reason for in-toeing. </li><li>Abnormal examination findings (for example rigid foot, asymmetric measurements, neurological deficiencies, or joint limitation; findings suggestive of cerebral palsy or developmental dysplasia of the hip — especially if there is a high risk birth history for neurological or orthopaedic impairment). </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 6613e968-61f9-4b8a-9b8e-aa0d00e65b15 --><!-- end item 3c22241d-80eb-4304-89d7-aa0d00e65b15 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"7d7efaae-cee9-515e-8485-fbc7c2560398","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-f87","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 698b7b00-d3e4-4218-a7fa-aa0d00e65b1c --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 698b7b00-d3e4-4218-a7fa-aa0d00e65b1c -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f874bfb6-04bb-4e31-bc31-aa0d00e65b1c --><!-- begin field 8c3ad457-91b1-46f1-9ef1-aa0d00e65b1c --><h4>Community management</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when community management is usually appropriate is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2019</a>]. <ul><li>Experts advise that benign in-toeing should not be referred to a specialist<strong> </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Berry, 2018</a>]. In one study of otherwise healthy children referred to an in-toeing clinic, more than 90% had a benign diagnosis and did not need treatment [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Davis and Nativio, 2018</a>].  A review article found no good evidence that interventions for paediatric in-toeing are beneficial [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Evans, 2017</a>].  </li></ul></li></ul><h4>Referral</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when to consider referral is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>],<strong> </strong>an explanation of the pGALS (paediatric Gait, Arms, Legs, and Spine) examination [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Foster, 2013</a>], and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Evans, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Berry, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Davis and Nativio, 2018</a>].<ul><li>A small proportion of children with in-toeing have an underlying condition and some will need review by an orthopaedic specialist [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Davis and Nativio, 2018</a>]. Although radiographs are not recommended for most children with in-toeing, they may be indicated in certain circumstances (for example to rule out hip dysplasia or other pathologic conditions) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Davis and Nativio, 2018</a>]. Red flag differential diagnoses listed by experts include infection and bone tumour [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Evans, 2017</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 8c3ad457-91b1-46f1-9ef1-aa0d00e65b1c --><!-- end item f874bfb6-04bb-4e31-bc31-aa0d00e65b1c -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}